# N243 | CPF80_Glue on the back surface of the panel

## Issue Description
- Issue: Glue on the back surface of the panel
- Model: C10.5
- Station: CPFILLING
- Machine: EQCPF00080
- Impact: 18 panel

## Customer Impact
- No impacts

## Containment Actions
- Stop machine and find root cause

## Timeline
- 21:30 10/06/2026
  - Machine running normal
- 22:00 10/06/2026
  - EQ replace valve as schedule
- 22:10 10/06/2026
  - Glue leakage but not check table center
- 22:15 10/06/2026
  - Machine continue production
- 04:00 11/06/2026
  - Detect glue on the back surface of the panel after curing
- 04:30 11/06/2026
  - EQ clean table center
  - Machine can continue production

## Symptom
- Glue was found on the back surface of panels after curing.
- 18 panels were impacted.
- Glue leakage happened earlier during valve replacement, but the center lift table was not checked at that time.

## FA & RC
- DL did not tighten the glue tube to the glue bottle securely when replacing the valve
- Glue leaked
- When the glue leakage occurred, DL did not check the table lift center and did not call IDL for checking this issue

### Conclusion
- Glue leaked onto table lift center, but it was not detected
- When panels passed through, glue stuck to the bottom / back surface

## Root Cause
- During valve replacement, DL did not tighten the glue tube to the glue bottle securely.
- Glue leaked onto the center lift table.
- The leakage on the table lift center was not checked and was not escalated for IDL inspection.
- When panels passed through the contaminated table lift center, glue transferred to the back surface of the panels.

## Failure Mechanism
- Valve replacement created a glue tube connection issue.
- Because the glue tube was not tightened securely, glue leaked out.
- The leaked glue contaminated the center lift table.
- Since the contamination was not detected immediately, production continued.
- Panels passing across the contaminated center lift table picked up glue on the back surface.
- The defect was only detected later after curing.

## Corrective Actions
1. Clean the surface of the center lift table → OK
2. Hand over the machine for PD team to recover production → OK

## Long-Term Corrective Actions
1. Train DL to check after tightening the glue tube to the glue bottle and chamber of valve → Done
2. Add glue tube connection confirmation to the FAI checklist → Done
3. Add 2 columns, “self check” and “cross check”, to the valve replacement checklist for signature verification during cross-check inspections → Done

## Current Status
- The contaminated center lift table was cleaned.
- Machine was handed over for production recovery.
- Training and checklist updates were completed.
- Production continued normally after cleaning.

## Impact
- Quality: 18 panels affected
- Production: temporary stop for root-cause finding and cleaning
- Safety: not stated in the slide
- Repeat risk: possible if glue tube tightening and post-replacement cross-check are not controlled

## Open Risk / Follow-up
- Need to keep glue tube connection confirmation in the FAI checklist
- Need to enforce self-check and cross-check signatures in valve replacement checklist
- Need to monitor repeat glue leakage after valve replacement activities

## Evidence
- Timeline shows glue leakage after scheduled valve replacement and later detection after curing
- FA & RC states:
  - DL did not tighten glue tube securely
  - glue leaked
  - table lift center was not checked
  - glue transferred to bottom / back surface of panels
- Corrective actions show center lift table cleaning and production recovery
- Long-term actions show training and checklist control updates
